<span id="iv.iv.iv.i-p84"></span> These colours entered into the
fashioning of the High Priest’s Ephod ([Exod.
28:5](../../../bib/kjv/exo028.htm#005.md),
[6](../../../bib/kjv/exo028.htm#006)<span id="iv.iv.iv.i-p84.1"></span>.md)
and the Vail of the Tabernacle. Probably a little symbolism was attached
to the ornaments of Ahasuerus’ palace of Susa, “where were white, green,
and blue” (or violet) “hangings fastened with cords of fine linen and
purple to silver rings and pillars of marble: the beds were of gold and
silver upon a pavement of red and blue and white and black marble.”
White and green might represent the earth, blue the air, purple the sea
and water generally, in the curtains: whilst in the variegated marble
pavement, red would naturally symbolize fire, blue the air, white water
(as colourless when pure), black earth (the soil). Notice “the air we
breathe,” etc.—“*Aëris quem spiramus et cujus carpimus flatum.*” Compare
Virgil, *Æn.* I. 387, 388.

